{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643663"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:55:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:55:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18002"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18002","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18002"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.1,0.02,0.08,0.74]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10716"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78843"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10716"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18002"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64192"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7302"},{"type":"tags","id":"7304"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24946"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24949"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27040"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78843"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures passes through the transverse foramina of the cervical vertebrae?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Brachial plexus","Carotid artery","Jugular vein","Spinal cord","Vertebral artery"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evertebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E is the structure that passes through the transverse foramina of the cervical vertebrae. These foramina are unique to the cervical spine and provide a protective passage for the vertebral arteries as they ascend to supply the posterior part of the brain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Espinal cord\u003C/strong\u003E passes through the vertebral foramen, not the transverse foramina. The vertebral foramen is the central opening in each vertebra that houses the spinal cord.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarotid artery\u003C/strong\u003E does not pass through the transverse foramina. It travels through the neck in a separate pathway and supplies blood to the anterior part of the brain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ejugular vein\u003C/strong\u003E also does not pass through the transverse foramina. It runs parallel to the carotid artery and drains blood from the brain back to the heart.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebrachial plexus\u003C/strong\u003E is a network of nerves that supplies the upper limb, and it does not pass through the transverse foramina. It travels through the neck and axilla, but not through the cervical vertebrae\u0027s transverse foramina.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The vertebral artery passes through the transverse foramina of the cervical vertebrae.","The transverse foramina are unique to the cervical vertebrae and are not present in thoracic or lumbar vertebrae.","The vertebral artery supplies blood to the posterior part of the brain."],"references":["Middleditch, A., \u0026 Oliver, J. (2005). Functional anatomy of the spine. Elsevier Health Sciences","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Bogduk, N. (2016). Functional anatomy of the spine. Handbook of clinical neurology, 136, 675-688","Adigun OO, Reddy V, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Back, Spinal Cord. 2023 Jun 26. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725689","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64192"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18002"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64192"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T21:15:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T21:15:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10716"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78843"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiovascular","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position"